b'To read more, The Blockchain is Still Waiting for its Web, Here is a Blueprint for Getting us There https://t.co/WUqyuNaMD9'
b'21/21 Now is the time to realize that the blockchain\xe2\x80\x99s future will depend on how well we expose its capabilities universally & openly.'
b'20/21 Will the sum of blockchain technologies turn into a giant Internet, or will their journey unfold as a messy and fragmented evolution?'
b'19/21 We can\xe2\x80\x99t force blockchain standards on the market, but the market needs to embrace standards over time.'
b'18/21 In 2017, we need to see serious discussions on universal standards, and real intentions from industry participants to work together.'
b'17/21 There are promising examples of blockchain related standards & we need to see more of them, e.g. IPFS for files and ERC20 for tokens.'
b'16/21 We need universal tools that no one owns, but that benefit everybody, similar to the Web technologies that liberated the Internet.'
b'15/21 A trust services layer could be that API veneer that homogenizes how we create, move, check, inspect, follow historical paths, etc.'
b'14/21 Blockchain browsers (B-Browsers) are going to be important, and we will start to see them in 2017.'
b'13/21 Blockchains could have a number of standards above the Internet\xe2\x80\x99s existing ones, allowing smooth bridging from one layer to another.'
b'12/21 The Internet and the Web have their standards. Where are the blockchain equivalent?'
b'11/21 Many areas ripe for standards: smart contracts, tokens, security, storage, messaging, identities, naming, record-keeping & more.'
b'10/21 In order to grow-up, blockchains will eventually need a lot of standards that are vendor and solutions agnostic.'
b'9/21 The state of collaboration between blockchains is plagued by timid efforts for building bridges and lateral co-operative capabilities.'
b'8/21 An engineer that knows how to program Bitcoin needs to relearn what they know, in order to develop on other blockchains.'
b'7/21 Unfortunately, blockchains don\xe2\x80\x99t have that luxury yet, as each platform has its own set of technologies and methods to work with.'
b'6/21 Since early days, the Internet and Web have matured nicely, and today rely on close to 200 standards across several layers.'
b'5/21 This scenario is not unlike the position the Internet was in, prior to the Web.'
b'4/21 With so much homogeneity in functionality intent, why so many different and incompatible blockchain technologies and software?'
b'3/21 The variety of available blockchains handle same few basic functions, recording (digital) value without needing a 3rd party to move it.'
b'2/21 What if blockchain tech is more like the Internet & we are still waiting for its Web layers, to fully exploit its capabilities?'
b'1/21 Maybe The Blockchain is Still Waiting for its Web. Here is Why in 20 points.'

b'11/11 Read more on Maximizing User Adoption by Understanding Behavioral Economics for Startups https://t.co/WJDE5Ipfdy'
b'10/11 Find your risk seeking segments of users (and there could be several of them), and you will get easier adoptions for your product.'
b'9/11 Understanding prospect theory is critical in finding your initial target segments, so you don\xe2\x80\x99t spin your wheels with the wrong ones.'
b'8/11 On your website & communications, highlight loss words & remind prospects wht they are \xe2\x80\x9cmissing out\xe2\x80\x9d v. wht they could be gaining.'
b'7/11 Break-up the different parts of your product & ask yourself: is this feature in the domain of risk aversion or risk seeking?'
b'6/11 Risk averse prospects are happy with their current situation and will push-back on your pitches and trials.'
b'5/11 Startups need to go after a segment of prospects that are risk-seekers: currently with no solution, or incurring losses.'
b'4/11 People strongly prefer avoiding losses to acquiring gains. Losses are twice as powerful as gains for moving people from status quo.'
b'3/11 People make decisions based on the potential value of losses and gains rather than the final outcome.'
b'2/11 Prospect theory is behavioral economic theory describing how people choose b/w alternatives that involve risk, with known outcomes.'
b"1/11 It's important to understand that \xe2\x80\x9cPeople tend to be risk-seeking in the domain of losses and risk-averse in the domain of gains\xe2\x80\x9d."
